I recently did the Dedicate series to get myself back into my yoga mindset, and it was so wonderful that I went back and started this one, True. I have been in my mind a lot lately, so have mostly been trying to focus on breath and body and just doing what I can each day to reconnect, but it is difficult for me. When I got to this video, and got to the end with the belly circles, I literally started crying. Part of the reason that I find it hard to drop into my body is because I've dealt with body image issues my whole life; but for some reason (and warning, hippy dippy stuff ahead), when I connected to my core and rubbed the belly that I try so hard to ignore, in that moment, I loved every inch of my stomach. It has nourished me, it has kept me strong, it has supported me, and all the while I have been hating it. Giving me that moment to really think about the most 'problematic' part of my body and how it is part of me as a whole and I should cherish it really struck me, and I'm grateful for this practice even more. Thanks, Adriene, for getting me to that lovely moment!
Work WITH your body; not ON it! YESSSSSSS!

Bit of a novel incoming, don't mind me...

I'm not unhealthy by any standards; I'm a dancer who works out several times a week, and though I don't eat as well as I want to, I still try to eat well. And because I've seen how much damage it's done to others in my life, I try my darnedest not to use weight (or, in my case specifically, perfect muscle tone) as the sole indicator of health. But I've been gaining weight over the last few years, basically since I've been out of college, and I've noticed it accumulating in my midsection, as tends to happen. So, as you might expect, I've developed some insecurities. I worry that I look mismatched with skinny arms, toned legs, and a bit of a "pouch"; I worry that other dancers will think I'm weak and my dancing won't be enough to make up for it; I worry that I'll only gain more and more weight no matter what I do and I'll never get the toned abs I want. These worries are compounding as I'm on a brief self-imposed hiatus from dance/intense exercise in order to heal some shin splints.

So the belly rub and body-positive talk at the end? Nearly made me tear up. I hadn't realized the extent to which I was/am alienating my stomach from the rest of me, and the extent to which I was/am working on my body instead of with it. It'll take some time to truly internalize that philosophy, of course, but I'm definitely grateful to you for putting it so impactfully. Thanks for making this series... I wanted to supplement my dancing with some yoga anyway, and I'm only six days in, but I think I'm going to genuinely try to make this a long-term thing. Anything that simultaneously gives me a workout and makes me think is a win in my book.
